0 0 18 18"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10.5 1a6.5 6.5 0 1 1-4.23 11.44l-4.42 4.41a.5.5 0 0 1-.7-.7l4.41-4.42A6.5 6.5 0 0 1 10.5 1zm0 1a5.5 5.5 0 1 0 0 11 5.5 5.5 0 0 0 0-11zm0 2c.28 0 .5.22.5.5V7h2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 .5.41v.09a.5.5 0 0 1-.5.5H11v2.5a.5.5 0 0 1-.41.5h-.09a.5.5 0 0 1-.5-.5V8H7.5a.5.5 0 0 1-.5-.41V7.5c0-.28.22-.5.5-.5H10V4.5a.5.5 0 0 1 .41-.5z"></path></svg></span></div><div style="padding-bottom:56.4%" class="image-hydration-wrapper sc-1eow4w5-3 iJyiXs"><div><img src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="Illustration for article titled The 50 most important American independent movies" data-srcset="https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fill,f_auto,fl_progressive,g_center,h_80,q_80,w_80/khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj.png 80w, https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fit,fl_progressive,q_80,w_320/khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj.png 320w, https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fit,f_auto,fl_progressive,q_80,w_470/khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj.png 470w, https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,fl_progressive,q_80,w_800/khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj.png 800w" draggable="auto" data-chomp-id="khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj" data-format="png" data-alt="Illustration for article titled The 50 most important American independent movies" data-anim-src=""/></div></div></span><figcaption class="no-caption sc-7s1ndr-0 fbAnrV">Photo<!-- -->: <!-- -->Trailer screenshot</figcaption></div><span data-id="khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj" data-recommend-id="image://khrahjzhkdvmhprfz4oj" data-format="png" data-width="1049" data-height="592" data-lightbox="true" data-recommended="false" class="js_recommend"></span></figure><p class="sc-77igqf-0 hJpRRP">So deeply has <em>Get Out</em> lodged itself in the cultural conversation—as a box office smash, as an Oscar winner, as the “social thriller” that turned writer-director Jordan Peele into a brand name unto himself—that it’s easy to forget its independent roots. This is the most galvanizing production so far from Blumhouse, a company that has become a horror behemoth by adhering to the indie ethos of giving ambitious filmmakers small but workable budgets and creative support. Some of the most provocative and influential independent films ever made have looked like genre exercises on the surface, a proud tradition that <em>Get Out</em> made even prouder. [Jesse Hassenger]<br/></p><div class="js_movable_ad_slot bxm4mm-7 bhZEGl"><div class="bxm4mm-9 jgnxje"><label class="bxm4mm-8 kLAkkQ">Advertisement</label><div is="bulbs-dfp" class="ad-container dfp dfp-slot-MID_BANNER ad-middleboard" data-ad-unit="MID_BANNER" data-targeting="{&quot;pos&quot;:&quot;mid_banner&quot;}"></div><div class="bt-wrapper"><span data-uid="5d1b8a6cd5-384" class="bt-uid-tg" style="display:none !important;text-align:center" data-css-selector="ad-container.ad-middleboard"></span></div></div></div></div><div class="sc-18b1b2r-5 ccAJCg"><div><h4 class="z1qon0-0 sHsHa">Share This Story</h4><div class="js_share-tools sc-18b1b2r-0 jZyWXs" data-position="bottom"><div class="sc-17x7c2u-2 gpwIdA"><a href="https://facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Ffilm.avclub.com%2Fthe-50-most-important-american-independent-movies-1842597128%3Futm_medium%3Dsharefromsite%26utm_source%3D_facebook" title="Share to Facebook" target="_blank" data-ga="[[&quot;Share Tools&quot;, &quot;Share to Facebook&quot;,&quot;bottom&quot;]]" class="sc-17x7c2u-0 gSzbYB"><span class="sc-17x7c2u-1 jBsDWZ"><span class="iyvn34-0 iSaTEN"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="18" height="18" aria-label="Facebook icon" viewBox="0 0 18 18"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M17 9.05A8.02 8.02 0 0 0 9 1C4.58 1 1 4.6 1 9.05A8.04 8.04 0 0 0 7.75 17v-5.62H5.72V9.05h2.03V7.28c0-2.02 1.2-3.14 3.02-3.14.88 0 1.8.16 1.8.16v1.98h-1.02c-.99 0-1.3.62-1.3 1.26v1.5h2.22l-.36 2.34h-1.86V17A8.04 8.04 0 0 0 17 9.05"></path></svg></span></span></a><a href="https://twitter.com/share?text=The%2050%20most%20important%20American%20independent%